# real-browser-mcp

MCP server + Chrome extension that gives AI agents control of the user's real browser (not headless). Two components that talk over WebSocket on localhost.

## Architecture

```
mcp-server/src/         TypeScript, compiled to mcp-server/dist/
  index.ts              Entry point, MCP registration, CLI --setup flag
  bridge.ts             WebSocket server, retry logic, ping/pong, per-tool timeouts
  tools/                One file per tool, exported via index.ts barrel
    types.ts            ToolDefinition interface, result helpers

extension/              Plain JS (not compiled), Chrome Manifest V3
  background.js         Service worker, WebSocket client, tool dispatch, reconnection
  content.js            Console capture only (no DOM helpers)
  popup/                Connection status UI with diagnostics log

agent-config/           Cursor rules, commands, Claude Code AGENTS.md, skills
  setup.mjs             npx real-browser-mcp --setup cursor|claude
```

## Two-Component System

The MCP server and Chrome extension are separate. The server runs via stdio (started by Cursor/Claude), the extension runs in Chrome. They connect over WebSocket.

- Server listens, extension connects as client
- Default port: 7225 (chosen to avoid CDP's 9222-9224 range and BrowserMCP's 9009)
- Port is configurable via WS_PORT env var (server) and extension popup (client)
- Both must use the same port or they won't connect

## Versioning

Versions jump by minor: 1.0.0, 1.1.0, 1.2.0, etc. Both package.json AND extension/manifest.json versions must stay in sync. Also update SERVER_VERSION in mcp-server/src/index.ts.

Three places to bump:
1. `package.json` "version"
2. `extension/manifest.json` "version"
3. `mcp-server/src/index.ts` SERVER_VERSION constant

## Publishing

npm package name matches directory name: `real-browser-mcp`.

```bash
npm run build
NPM_CONFIG_USERCONFIG=/tmp/.npmrc-publish npm publish --access public
```

The npm package includes: mcp-server/dist/, extension/, agent-config/, LICENSE, README.md.
The extension is NOT on Chrome Web Store - users load it unpacked.

## Adding a New Tool

1. Create `mcp-server/src/tools/<name>.ts` with a ToolDefinition export
2. Add handler function in `extension/background.js` dispatch() map
3. Export from `mcp-server/src/tools/index.ts`
4. Add test in `tests/tools/`

Tool schemas use `z.ZodObject<z.ZodRawShape>` (not plain ZodType) because the MCP SDK expects `.shape` property.

## Testing

```bash
npm test              # vitest run, 26 tests
npm run typecheck     # tsc --noEmit
```

Tests use unique ports (19230+) via a counter to avoid conflicts between parallel test runs. Bridge tests need port isolation because WebSocket servers take time to unbind.

## Key Decisions Made

- Port 7225: avoids Chrome DevTools Protocol range (9222-9224) and BrowserMCP (9009). Not registered in IANA.
- No `debugger` permission in extension: was in the original project but never used. Highly privileged, removed.
- Content script is minimal: only captures console. All DOM interaction uses chrome.scripting.executeScript from background.js.
- Accessibility tree snapshot assigns `data-mcp-ref` attributes (e12, e13...) for element targeting. Refs are invalidated after navigation or scroll.
- Cursor deeplink for one-click install: `cursor://anysphere.cursor-deeplink/mcp/install?name=real-browser&config=<base64>`

## Extension Debugging

- Extension errors: chrome://extensions > Real Browser MCP > Errors
- Background script console: chrome://extensions > Real Browser MCP > "Inspect views: service worker"
- Popup shows: connection state (connected/reconnecting/error), attempt count, retry countdown, event log
- Common error: "EADDRINUSE" means another process already has the port. Kill it or change WS_PORT.
- Common error: "ERR_CONNECTION_REFUSED" means the MCP server isn't running. Check Cursor MCP settings.
